results.notes:
Fruiting on dead wood(woodchips) in natural habitat beneath Douglas fir and Western red cedar.
NON-BURNED HABITAT.
Caps: tacky, viscid, glutinous(note abundant needle litter attached to specimens).
Incurved margins, becoming somewhat plane with central broadly umbonate disc.
Young caps are ochre, chestnut and more orange toward center.
Mature caps are deeply ferruginous(Maroon orange brown).
Gills: starting pale brown/white. Dull brown at maturity.
Stem: covered in dense scales(like Pholiota terrestris). Scales beginning at veil attachment and continuing downward. Stem apex smooth and tapered above veil remnant zone.
Scales initially whitish, staining yellow were handled and brownish at base. White mycelium attached to bark at base.
Stems are thick, cylindrical. Context faintly pale yellow but mostly white.
Odor: pleasant, nearly cinnamon like.
Taste: mild.
Harvested 8 specimens.
Spore printed a section of cap directly on glass slide for print:
Spore Print: darkish cinnamon brown.
Spores: inamyloid in Lugolâ€™s.
Microscopy:
Mounted 2 gills in KOH:
Basidia: 4 spored. See images.
Pleurocystidia: abundant, fusoid to ventricose.
Cheilocystidia: large, fusiform to lageniform, many adorned with crystalline elements near apex. See images.
Lamellar trama: short, stubby interwoven hyphae.
Mounted another slide with cap tissue to analyze Pileipellis:
Exterior hyphae: ixocutis cylindrical hyphae encrusted with small elements.
Epicutis: gelatinous layer of a pressed/interwoven hyphae.
Interior hyphae(trama): cells swollen, inflated, clamp connections present. Images included.
Spores: smooth, small, dull brown to lighter golden in KOH. Elliptical to ovoid, slightly thick walled. Side laying spores are slightly curved.
Small apical germ pore.
Dehydrated all specimens and bagged for herbarium collection/genetic record.
Caps dehydrated deep brownish maroon.
